description.text:
This is a mouse pad designed to fit over the side drawer of a desk. It's fairly large so i designed it in four pieces and they will need to be glued together. The full dimensions are around 11.75" x 9.2" (internal lip for drawer is 9.625"). Included in the design I've built in mounting/locking brackets that can be used as glue points. The front lip of the pad is designed to sit over the top of the drawer.

This should be able to be scaled to pretty much any drawer. Additionally I've included my CAD file if you would rather work with that.

This is my first home built design and I can see definite improvements I can make to cut down on how much filament is used - so I probably will upload updated files in the future. In the meantime however, enjoy.

description.text:
Tips are always appreciated!

In the army we used to hold the straps down with black insulation tape, but now I don't really want to get my bag straps sticky anymore.

At first, I used the rubber bands that came with my bag but I found that gradually one of the bag straps would get longer than the other. It got annoying having to readjust my bag every week or so, so I decided to take advantage of some TPU filament I acquired to make this.

The internal diameter is 13mm x 21mm. Printed in TPU (clear), 215 deg, 0.4mm nozzle, 100% infill, 40mm/s, 80deg glass HBP with blue painter's tape. I find that 1 layer thickness of TPU makes it super strechy, 2 layers makes it harder, 3 layers makes it quite a bit more rigid. This has 3 total shells if I am not wrong. (EDIT: On second thought I can't remember anything about this setting, I made this a month back and my printer has been down for a while, either I'm right about this or I'm just throwing random figures that I rememeber to be true but might not actually be true)

This holds 4 to 5 rolls of the bag strap nicely, and it's not come loose since I started using this.

I suggest scaling up or down the item to suit your requirements. If you need something more specific designed, do let me know and I'll try and help out where I can.

title: My Simplify3D profiles for the FlashForge Creator Pro

description.text:
This is not a printable thing, it is my version of best settings for the FlashForge Creator Pro printer, the 10mm cube was added to satisfy the need for a 3D file!

I decided to post the custom profiles I use for the Simplify3D software on my FlashForge Creator Pro. If you have not tried the Simplify3D software I encourage you to check it out as it is very versatile software and can help improve the quality of your prints regardless of the printer you own. It is expensive at $150 USD but well worth it, they have a 2 week trial so you can see if it meets your needs.

If you have a FlashForge Creator Pro and use Simplify3D I welcome you to import these profiles and try them out. I have changed the startup Gcode script so that the printer head stays in the back right corner (when looking from front) while heating up and then extruding a somewhat thick line on the back edge of the build plate about a third of the width of the build plate to purge the extruder before printing. I have also tweaked various speed settings as well as heat settings for various types of filament, the "standard plastics" file contains speed/temp settings for standard plastics like ABS and PLA and the "flex materials" file contains speed/temp settings for flexible filaments like TPU/Ninjaflex.

These are simply the settings that worked best for me, please feel free to modify them to your liking and post a remix or make so that others may be able to benefit from settings you have found work best.

title: Reversible lens hood for Fuji 35mm F/1.4

description.text:
Why?

If you own a Fuji mirrorless lens you know how beautiful the metal square lens hoods are.

Sadly you'll also know how annoying they are, because they can't be reversed for transport and you have to take them off to remove the lens cap. My lens hood fixes both of those problems.

Features:

  • The hood can be mounted in reverse to go around the lens barrel, making it easier to transport your camera in a small bag

  • The lens cap can be placed or removed when the hood is mounted.

  • Uses existing threads on your lens barrel

  • Features a notch that lines up with the white notch on the lens when mounting

  • Long enough to prevent lens flare, short enough to prevent vignetting.

Instructions:

Rotate clockwise to mount, counter-clockwise to dismount.
Print in black, matte filament for best results. I recommend PETG for strength/flexibility.
Print with supports under the upper set of threads!

Open source

Update 06/03/2017
Found that after a few reel changes and using the 3D printed spindle that it was somewhat loose. My answer was to drill a 3mm hole in the outer cone and then use a tap to give it a good thread and used a 3mm plastic screw. Only finger tightness is needed and the cones now sit with no slippage on the spindle.

Needed something to centre the filament reels I have. The centre of the reels are mostly different sizes so came up with this little paraboloid shape in Tinkercad. It can handle my reels which have central holes from 30mm up to 55mm. Then added the hole for the 8mm threaded bar.

Soon found out that the threaded bar likes to rotate and trap the spool against the spool holder making the printer struggle to get the filament. Tinkercad again came to the rescue with the 8mm x 165mm spindle. Found that once you insert one cone onto the reel and then add the spindle and then add the last cone on the other end the reel still like to travel. Ending up with the reel rolling around the work top.

Maybe I should make the spindle a little longer. So used a couple of mistake cones which I had onto the spindle, one on each side and this keeps the reel centred on the reel holder which came with the 3D printer.

description.text:
A simple travel sized rubberband loom hook. The hook is an essential rubberband loom accessory that prints in minutes. Print a quick replacement for this easily lost item. Create a compact travel craft kit or perfect stocking stuffer by combining this design and the customizable rubber band loom fishtail maker (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:165857). Place the hook, loom and craft rubber bands in a sandwich bag for crafting on the go. Store bought rubberband looms are big with lots of parts. The travel size hook and loom (thing:165857) fit easily in a purse, backpack or pocket. Rubberband crafting is a craze among elementary kids this year. Do yourself a favor and print out a kit for all the kids you know. These will be a hit at holiday parties and the long days off over break. P.S. You don't need an expensive loom to get kids started, two nails in a board creates a quick beginnner's loom. Please leave a comment or contact me on Twitter @DesignMakeTeach or on Facebook at Facebook.com/DesignMakeTeach.I love to talk with teachers, designers and makers about 3D printing and Learning by Making.
Visit my blog at DesignMakeTeach.com

Depending on the resolution of your print, the hook may have a sharp end. The sharp end is useful for sliding between rubberbands especially in the more complex designs. If the hook is too sharp for younger hands then you can snap, clip or file down the point.

description.text:
This is a remix from McMuffin77 excellent Arkham Horror Portal. I found his model pleasing to the eye, but way to much for the capabilities of my printer
I used his tentacles and resized them to be bigger and less prone to break off during handling. Also i re-positioned and turned them so they support each other and had angles more to the liking off my printer/filament. The base and back plate i had to redesign, but stayed close to the original.
However, this is still quite some feat for an fdm-type 3D-printer to print. It will put a lot of stress on the mechanics while printing, especially when you are using retracts. You have been warned, don't expect something super smooth.

WARNING

DISCLAIMER

This Thing comes as it is. I'm not responsible for any damage, nor do i garantiue that this will work.

INTRODUCTION

This Thing is to upgrade the gantry of an 3D-Printer with linearguide rails and corexy mechanics. The 3D-Printer needs to be based around 20mm aluminium extrusion profiles. Also this thing does nothing to your z-axis. The BOM includes all required parts, some of which you can probably reuse from the base printer.

I shot some linearguide Rails on ebay to upgrade my cheap chinese 3D-printer kit. Unfortunatetly i got the rails from different manufacturers. As the carriages differ from hiwin and PMI, you need to edit a few pieces if you go all hiwin or all PMI. And yes, i know that 15mm rails are just plain overkill.

I decided to put the Y-rails underneath the aluminium profiles

BOM

see attached file

SAFETY ADVISE

I'll recommend to print all parts except the corner brackets with ABS, ASA or any other Filament that has some temperature resistance. The corner bracket (with integrated idler plates and motor mounts) can be printed with ABS as well, but the extra stiffness from PLA would be beneficial to your belt tension. Also you should use a bright color, i.e. white. Especially the parts close to your hotend can be damaged from the heat over time. The bright color ensures that you can easily recognize burnt parts before something ignites. If printed in black, you will have a hard time finding scorched spots.

Before assembly make sure you cover any glas bed surface with a cardboard. Screws and tools will obey gravity and probably damage or break the bed surface.

Have you ever put together one of those wire shelving units where the shelves are held up by these flimsy plastic pieces that snap on to the side of the posts?  Have you broken those flimsy plastic pieces in the process?  Now you don't need to wrap the post in duct tape and ignore the fact that its been lopsided for the last year.

These pieces are a simple two halved tapered cylinder, with tabs to snap them together and a small inner ring to grip the groove in the post.  The measurements are currently to fit my unit and aren't likely to fit yours, so change the variables at the top of the scad file to match yours and re-render.
Just print out as many as you need to hold up your shelves, snap them onto the side of the post and slide the shelves down onto them.  They don't actually need to be that strong, the compression from the tapered tube on this type of shelf is what provides most of the force to hold it up.  I printed mine out of PLA and they have proven to be far more sturdy than the originals.

title: MP Mini Modified Right Side for 30mm Fan

description.text:
I tried to adapt Thing 1873935 to use the 30mm fan I had laying around. It didn't come out the way I hoped. So I grabbed my trusty millimeter ruler, took some measurements and started from scratch. The result is this two piece side assembly. It seemed to me that the fan would pull cooler air from the vents on the bottom of the printer so I didn't add any extra openings. I mounted the fan so it would be close to the main board and blowing out. The two pieces should snap together, although I had to trim mine a tad.

The glitch in the fan grid in the photo was caused by me. I forgot to set the fill for 100%.. Hollow spokes that small don't hold up well. The assembly as a whole ain't pretty, but it does the job.

A case for Orange Pi Lite, I use it for OctoPrint.
It has a hole at the top that is tight enough to hold the antenna in place. It is a tight fit, no need for screws. And as you can see from the images the camera interface, GPIO pins, IR receiver and reset button are not usable.

You might want to add four legs at the bottom to allow air to flow in, if you do a lot of RAM access, at least for OctoPrint this is not necessary.

Printer:

Qidi Avatar IV

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm layer height

Infill:

No

Notes:

Prints fine with ABS.
If you need additional support add a 2..5 mm wide and 0.2 mm height border around the two case parts, and rotate the object by 45° for faster printing (as I've done in the lua script).

I took the caliper and measured the Orange Pi Lite board including connectors and antenna. From these measurements I created a first model of the Orange Pi Lite. Then I created the case, with base and top, using the first model as negative form.
To allow for some inaccuracy for measurements and printing I created, based on the first model, a second model of the Orange Pi Lite with slightly larger connectors. And finally I used this second model as negative form to create base and top.
It's created in IceSL, you can download the application here https://members.loria.fr/Sylvain.Lefebvre/icesl/ or just use it online at http://shapeforge.loria.fr/icesl-online/ .
I created g-code with slic3r and IceSL, both print well (You might want to rotate the top part 180° to print it).
